amily Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Waller","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: occupational name from Middle English <i>waler</i>, <i>waliere</i>, <i>walour</i>, <i>waller</i> ‘builder of walls, mason’.","English: in Sussex, perhaps a topographic name for someone who lived by a prominent wall.","English: topographic name for someone who lived by a spring, stream, or man-made well, from Middle English <i>waller</i>, a derivative of Middle English <i>walle</i>, Old English <i>wælle</i>, <i>wælle</i>. It is a West Midlands dialect form of   Weller  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Wallar","meanings":["English: variant of   Waller  ."]},{"name":"Weller","meanings":["English (Surrey, Sussex, and Kent): topographic name for someone who lived by a spring, stream, or man-made well, from Middle English <i>weller</i>, <i>willer</i>, an agent derivative of Middle English <i>welle</i> (in southern England) and <i>wille</i> (in south western England), from Old English <i>wella</i>, <i>well(e)</i>, <i>wiella</i>, <i>wielle</i>, <i>willa</i>, <i>wyll(a)</i>, <i>wylle</i>. This type of name, a topographic term + <i>-er</i>, is particularly typical of Sussex and its neigbouring counties.","English: occupational name for someone who casts metal or who boils salt, from Middle English <i>weller</i>, <i>willer</i>, a derivative with <i>-er</i> of Old English <i>wellan</i>, <i>wiellan</i> ‘to boil’. Compare 5 below.","North German: variant of   Welle  , cognate with 1 above."]}]},{"name":"Walter","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French personal name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>wald</i> ‘rule’ + <i>heri</i>, <i>hari</i> ‘army’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, superseding the native Old English form, <i>Wealdhere</i>. It was a very popular name in medieval England, normally pronounced ‘Water’."],"variants":[{"name":"Walther","meanings":["from <i>wald</i> ‘rule’ + <i>heri</i> ‘army’; name of the famous medieval minnesinger  Walther von der Vogelweide  (  <i>c.</i>1170– <i>c.</i>1230 )."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705188,"age":5,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705189,"age":40,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705190,"age":71,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705191,"age":96,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Walter de Waller was born on 8 January 1218, in Hockerton, Nottinghamshire, England as the son of William de Waller. He married Agatha de Thorpe about 1237, in Hockerton, Nottinghamshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died on 6 January 1316, in Southwell, Nottinghamshire, England, at the age of 97."},"et":{"8 January 1218–6 January 1316":"8. jaanuar 1218–6. jaanuar 1316","1218–1316":"1218–1316","1220–1316":"1220–1316","1240–1271":"1240–1271","1187–1274":"1187–1274","1187":"1187","1220":"1220","1274":"1274","1240":"1240","6 January 1316":"6. jaanuar 1316","1271":"1271","8 January 1218":"8. jaanuar 1218","1290":"1290","1316":"1316","1315":"1315","1259":"1259","4 July 1274":"4. juuli 1274","1224":"1224","about 1237":"umbes 1237","1317":"1317","1218":"1218","Somerton, Suffolk, England":"Somerton, Suffolk, England","Southwell, Nottinghamshire, England":"Southwell, Nottinghamshire, England","England":"England","Hockerton, Nottinghamshire, England":"Hockerton, Nottinghamshire, England"},"fi":{"8 January 1218–6 January 1316":"8. tammikuuta 1218–6. tammikuuta 1316","1218–1316":"1218–1316","1220–1316":"1220–1316","1240–1271":"1240–1271","1187–1274":"1187–1274","1187":"1187","1220":"1220","1274":"1274","1240":"1240","6 January 1316":"6. tammikuuta 1316","1271":"1271","8 January 1218":"8. tammikuuta 1218","1290":"1290","1316":"1316","1315":"1315","1259":"1259","4 July 1274":"4. heinäkuuta 1274","1224":"1224","about 1237":"noin 1237","1317":"1317","1218":"1218","Somerton, Suffolk, England":"Somerton, Suffolk, England","Southwell, Nottinghamshire, England":"Southwell, Nottinghamshire, England","England":"England","Hockerton, Nottinghamshire, England":"Hockerton, Nottinghamshire, England"},"fr":{"8 January 1218–6 January 1316":"8 janvier 1218–6 janvier 1316","1218–1316":"1218–1316","1220–1316":"1220–1316","1240–1271":"1240–1271","1187–1274":"1187–1274","1187":"1187","1220":"1220